.SH NAME
nog \- tier-aware package manager for KognogOS
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nog
.I <command>
.RI [ options ]
.RI [ packages ]
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B nog
is the package manager for KognogOS. It wraps
.BR pacman (8)
\(em and optionally an AUR helper such as
.BR yay (8)
or
.BR paru (8)
\(em with a three-tier update management system, giving every package on the
system a protection level based on how critical it is.
.PP
Tier 1 packages (the kernel, bootloader, glibc, systemd, mesa) are held for
30 days after upstream publish before auto-releasing. Tier 2 packages are
held for 15 days. Tier 3 packages are held for 7 days. Expert users can
switch Tier 1 to a manual-sign-off mode via
.B tier-pins.toml
if they prefer to eyeball every kernel upgrade personally. See
.B TIER SYSTEM
for the full model.
.PP
.B nog
should always be run as your regular user. It escalates to root only where
genuinely required — by invoking
.B sudo pacman
for package transactions and
.B sudo tee
for writing
.IR /etc/nog/tier-pins.toml .
See the
.B PRIVILEGES AND SUDO
section below for the complete privilege model.
.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B nog install \fIpackage\fR [\fIpackage\fR...]
Install one or more packages. Tier classification is printed as informational
output; installs are never blocked or gated — explicit user commands execute
user intent. If an AUR helper is configured (see
.BR nog.conf (5)),
the install routes through the helper, so AUR-only packages work transparently
without any pre-check. Tier protection applies to future updates, not to installs.
.TP
.B nog remove \fIpackage\fR [\fIpackage\fR...]
Remove one or more packages via
.BR pacman (8).
Works uniformly for packages originally installed from official repos or AUR.
.TP
.B nog update
Compute a tier-aware system upgrade plan and hand it off to
.BR pacman (8)
or the configured AUR helper. Every pending upgrade is shown before any
transaction starts, classified into one of three buckets:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B Ready to install
\(em hold window has expired; safe to upgrade
.IP \(bu 2
.B Held
\(em still within the tier's hold window, or Tier 1 package with
.B manual_signoff = true
.IP \(bu 2
.B Unknown
\(em no resolvable build date (locally built, disabled repo, or helper lookup failed)
.RE
Each
.B Unknown
package triggers an interactive
.B "[y/N]"
prompt. Pending official repo upgrades come from
.BR checkupdates (8);
pending AUR upgrades come from
.B "<helper> -Qua" .
Build dates come from the enabled pacman sync databases and, for AUR packages
not found in any sync DB, from the helper's cached metadata (\fB<helper> -Sai\fR).
The final transaction invokes
.B pacman
or the helper with
.B --ignore=
listing all held and user-skipped packages.
.TP
.B nog search \fIquery\fR
Search for packages matching
.IR query
via
.BR pacman (8).
Each result is annotated by tier using the Catppuccin Mocha palette
(red Tier 1, yellow Tier 2, green Tier 3).
.TP
.B nog pin \fIpackage\fR \fB--tier=\fR\fI<1|2|3>\fR
Pin a package to a specific tier. The change is written to
.IR /etc/nog/tier-pins.toml
via
.B sudo tee
and survives reboots. Pinning to Tier 3 removes any existing Tier 1 or Tier 2
entry for that package (Tier 3 is the implicit default for anything not listed).
.TP
.B nog unlock \fIpackage\fR [\fB--promote\fR]
Without
.BR --promote ,
this command is informational only. Tier 1 packages under
.B manual_signoff = true
are held wholesale; there is no per-session unlock state to toggle, so this
mode simply prints the held status and points at
.BR --promote .
With
.BR --promote ,
force-upgrade the package immediately via
.BR pacman (8)
or the configured helper, bypassing the hold window and any sign-off policy.
This is the escape hatch for a held Tier 1 package.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Print help information.
.TP
.B \-V, \-\-version
Print version information.
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/nog/nog.conf
Main nog configuration file. Defines paths, hold windows (\fB[holds]\fR), and
AUR helper preference (\fB[aur]\fR).
.TP
.I /etc/nog/tier-pins.toml
Tier assignments for all managed packages. Edited by
.B nog pin
(written via
.BR "sudo tee" )
or manually by the system administrator.
.B manual_signoff
under
.B [tier1]
controls whether Tier 1 auto-releases (default) or stays wholesale held
(expert mode).
.TP
.I /var/lib/pacman/sync/*.db
Pacman sync databases. Read-only by nog, for build-date lookup during
.BR "nog update" .
.TP
.I /etc/pacman.conf
Read-only. nog parses it for enabled repositories and their priority order.
.TP
.I /usr/bin/nog
The nog binary.
.
.SH TIER SYSTEM
Every package nog manages is classified into one of three tiers, defined in
.IR /etc/nog/tier-pins.toml .
Each tier has a hold window (from the
.B [holds]
section of
.IR /etc/nog/nog.conf )
that must elapse after the package's upstream publish date before the update is
applied during
.BR "nog update" .
.SS Tier 1 \(em 30-day hold, auto-release by default
The most critical packages: kernel, bootloader, glibc, systemd, mesa. By default
(\fBmanual_signoff = false\fR), Tier 1 auto-releases after a 30-day hold window
\(em a full month of community testing before an update lands on your system.
.PP
Expert mode: set
.B manual_signoff = true
under
.B [tier1]
in
.IR tier-pins.toml
to switch Tier 1 to always-held; updates release only via
.B "nog unlock <pkg> --promote" .
Recommended only for users who want to review every kernel / glibc / systemd
upgrade personally.
.PP
Default Tier 1 packages:
.BR linux ", " linux-zen ", " linux-lts ", " linux-hardened ", " systemd ", "
.BR systemd-libs ", " glibc ", " grub ", " efibootmgr ", " mkinitcpio ", "
.BR pacman ", " mesa .
.SS Tier 2 \(em 15-day hold
Key desktop applications and system services. Held for 15 days after upstream
publish \(em enough time for major regressions to surface without falling far behind.
.PP
Default Tier 2 packages:
.BR plasma-meta ", " plasma-desktop ", " sddm ", " pipewire ", " pipewire-pulse ", "
.BR wireplumber ", " networkmanager ", " firefox ", " dolphin ", " konsole ", "
.BR kate ", " grubforge ", " alacritty ", " fish ", " alacrittyforge .
.SS Tier 3 \(em 7-day hold
Everything else. A short 7-day safety buffer without meaningful delay. Anything
not listed in Tier 1 or Tier 2 falls into Tier 3 automatically.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Install a package (nog prompts for sudo itself if needed):
.B nog install htop
.TP
Update the system:
.B nog update
.TP
Search with tier annotations:
.B nog search firefox
.TP
Pin a package to Tier 2:
.B nog pin htop --tier=2
.TP
Force-upgrade a held Tier 1 package:
.B nog unlock linux-zen --promote
.
.SH PRIVILEGES AND SUDO
.B nog
itself always runs as the invoking user; it is not designed to be run with
.BR sudo .
If you prefix
.B sudo nog
while an AUR helper is configured, nog detects the invocation (via
.B $SUDO_USER
or
.BR $SUDO_UID )
and exits with an error, because
.BR yay (8)
and
.BR paru (8)
refuse to run as root.
.PP
nog escalates to root in exactly two places, both as transparent
.BR sudo (8)
subprocess invocations:
.TP
.B sudo pacman -S | -R | -Syu ...
For package transactions during
.BR install ,
.BR remove ,
.BR update ,
and
.B "unlock --promote"
\(em but only when no AUR helper is configured. When a helper is configured,
nog hands the transaction to the helper (as the invoking user), and the
helper runs its own
.B sudo pacman
internally for the pacman step.
.TP
.B sudo tee /etc/nog/tier-pins.toml
For the single file
.B nog
ever writes. Used only during
.BR "nog pin" .
The new file contents are rebuilt in memory and piped through
.BR tee ;
nog itself never runs with root privileges.
.PP
.B nog
never modifies any other file on your system \(em not
.IR /etc/pacman.conf ,
not
.IR /etc/pacman.d/ ,
not
.IR /var/lib/pacman/local/ ,
not the pacman keyring, and not
.IR /etc/sudoers .
It is a thin wrapper over
.BR pacman (8),
.BR yay (8),
or
.BR paru (8);
every install, remove, and upgrade is subject to pacman's signature
verification and conflict resolution, which nog cannot bypass.
.
